00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.280
First, let's have a look at 
what these things really are.

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:38.960
That is, of course, from being 
life-changing for some of our colleagues,

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:45.840
vital learning tools, and increasingly 
essential for search engines.

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:55.440
Basically, if you don't have that 
subtitle this is what is going to happen:

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:01.520
People won't be able to access 
it in a variety of mediums,

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:06.800
and search engines certainly can't. We'll be 
talking more about that through this presentation.

00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:15.360
Now, we often come across two terms of subtitles 
and captions as if they mean the same thing.

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:21.200
But there are actually three terms that 
are widely used in the media production.

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:30.720
Subtitles, open captions, and closed captions as you 
can see on the screen. That's what the technical

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:38.000
definition is. They do not actually mean the same 
thing. At the moment there are three main types.

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:44.880
We'll come to images and the new type 
of captioning that is coming in later on.

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:53.920
Fundamentally they all mean a visual on-screen 
text representation of the words heard in an audio

00:04:53.920 --> 00:05:02.000
track, or a video, or your broadcast. You'll often 
hear - hear these terms interchangeably, but you do

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:07.600
need to know which of the terms that you actually 
need for your product and your organization,

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:12.640
depending on the environment, and the ecosystem,
the regulatory framework that you're operating in.

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:21.280
So captions come in two varieties - open or 
closed. Both go further than simple subtitling.

00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:29.840
They not only represent the spoken words, but they 
include text descriptions of all non-verbal sounds

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:36.480
which may form part of that presentation. So 
captions amplify the dialogue, the narrative,

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:41.840
with descriptions of sounds that would be included 
through the subtitling of that spoken language.

00:05:42.400 --> 00:05:48.880
So, for example: woman coughs loudly;
sound of breaking glass; dog barks.

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:58.400
(I always wait for my dog to actually see that as a 
command.); doorbell rings; music plays. This is to try

00:05:58.400 --> 00:06:06.240
and get as much closely to the atmosphere and feel 
of the audio track. It's much more interesting for

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:13.120
the person who can't access the words or the sound, 
to have a better idea of what is being represented.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.840
Providing captions can have a greater 
implication on production time,

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:27.120
and costs and subtitling. But both continue 
to become easier to create and synchronize

00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:31.680
through the development of enabling software 
and artificial intelligence. As a firm,

00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:36.960
we do a lot of work in this area, and it's so 
wonderful to see it becoming more accessible.

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:43.280
I've mentioned two forms of captions. Open 
captions are captions embedded in the video at

00:06:43.280 --> 00:06:50.240
production stage, and are on screen permanently. The 
viewer cannot choose whether they appear or not.

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:55.520
We've - I've kept this slide up, because when I've 
done this presentation before, people have said

00:06:55.520 --> 00:07:01.600
they felt it was easier for them to, to 
understand the difference when we have this up. So

00:07:01.600 --> 00:07:08.160
..um, closed captions are interactive in what they 
can be turned off or on or off at the choice of

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:15.520
the viewer. A quick toggle of the remote control 
and, hey, presto - captions on, captions off. A bit like

00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:23.280
the mute button for audio volume. Captions can be a 
legal requirement in some jurisdictions for videos

00:07:23.280 --> 00:07:28.560
intended to be broadcast in public, and they're 
enforced through the various countries legal

00:07:28.560 --> 00:07:33.920
systems. As ever I would urge you to look 
at the regulations in your own jurisdiction  -

00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:38.480
and you may find these in a variety of 
places, from broadcasting legislation,

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:45.680
equality, anti-discrimination regulations, to 
communications and media laws - but also in the

00:07:45.680 --> 00:07:51.840
ethos and values of your own organization. The penalties for infringement can be high,

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:59.680
and it's worth including the captions and 
subtitles in your initial brief, in your scoping.

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:08.160
In some locations require - the requirements 
apply to both public bodies and organizations

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:13.520
with registered charitable status, so do your 
homework. Check it what it is that you need.

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:22.640
So, apart from legal compliance where it 
applies, why, why should we provide subtitles

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:30.400
and captions? Well, subtitling is a way to make that 
video material more accessible. It actually makes

00:08:30.400 --> 00:08:36.240
it possible for some one with a hearing difficulty 
to hear the message behind the video at all.

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:45.600
But there are a lot of myths about subtitling and 
why you shouldn't do it, so hopefully today we'll

00:08:45.600 --> 00:08:52.800
debunk some of those myths. Hearing disabilities 
can be caused by a large variety of reasons, from

00:08:52.800 --> 00:09:00.560
disabilities from birth, trauma, injury related, and 
from actually just getting older, as well as health

00:09:00.560 --> 00:09:06.400
related issues. They may be temporary, they may be 
permanent. We have a number of colleagues in my

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:14.240
work and in the WordPress community who have some kind of hearing impairment. In our work in both of

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:21.200
these areas we've been running awareness surveys 
around what people think subtitles are for. Our

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:27.200
