00:23:45.040 --> 00:23:54.720
Captioning allows that to happen better. We've 
talked about the bots, but just to reinforce it -

00:23:54.720 --> 00:23:59.040
Search, search, search. They don't understand 
it. If they've got no value they will move on.

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:09.360
I'm going to take you down to what's 
happening now with artificial intelligence. As

00:24:09.360 --> 00:24:15.040
with all things tech related, times move on and 
processes are in a state of constant evolution.

00:24:16.080 --> 00:24:22.560
Captioning for the last 10 years or so has used 
differing technologies including automated speech

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:30.720
recognition known as ASR. ASR is a predictive tool.
It generates word sequences from an audio signal.

00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:35.840
The result is not always a totally 
accurate rendition of what is being said.

00:24:36.880 --> 00:24:40.800
The nature of live streaming, especially,
where conversation is interactive,

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:49.440
presents challenges to ASR. Not all speakers will 
be clear enough in their delivery. Background

00:24:49.440 --> 00:24:54.960
noises in their environment can seem like a 
verbal sound to be represented in captions to ASR.

00:24:56.160 --> 00:24:59.840
How well has it been taught to 
differentiate between sounds.

00:25:01.040 --> 00:25:07.120
If discussions get heated, people may speak over 
each other or cut another speaker off abruptly.

00:25:07.840 --> 00:25:14.560
Again, resulting in a muddled set of captions.
In fac,t you don't even need that to happen -

00:25:14.560 --> 00:25:19.840
you can just have lots of different voices 
that are similar and ASR may not pick it up.

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:27.840
Strong regional or national accents, or varieties 
of inflection from different speakers can confuse

00:25:27.840 --> 00:25:34.800
ASR, and result in misrepresentation in captioning. 
I'm sure we've all sat through presentations, even

00:25:34.800 --> 00:25:41.840
TV programs, where the captioning has been so 
obviously incorrect it can almost be comical.

00:25:42.720 --> 00:25:48.400
Except for those who rely on it. For 
them it really is not a laughing matter.

00:25:50.800 --> 00:25:57.120
You'll all probably be aware of the variety 
of accuracies and inaccuracies delivered by

00:25:57.120 --> 00:26:03.600
today's range of streaming platforms in terms of 
captioning. The consequences of misrepresentation

00:26:03.600 --> 00:26:10.160
via captioning are the same as the consequences 
of mistranslating between two languages.

00:26:10.160 --> 00:26:16.960
To be effective, the ASR system, like Web 
Captioner and others, needs to have been prepped

00:26:16.960 --> 00:26:24.800
with a wide vocabulary and specialist words. It 
can also be taught to learn in multiple languages,

00:26:25.360 --> 00:26:31.360
and any specialist acronyms, jargon, tech 
terminology, and so on which it might encounter.

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:40.320
If it doesn't recognize the content of the source 
signal, it cannot predict the patterns of words. You

00:26:40.320 --> 00:26:47.040
will sometimes see a "next best" word or phrase 
appear, which of course will often make a nonsense

00:26:47.040 --> 00:26:56.960
version of the original. So one of the most often 
questions I get is, "Oh, I've added AI to my streams,

00:26:56.960 --> 00:27:03.520
I've added, um, an automatic captioner, that's all 
I need to do." No. You need to train it. You need

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:11.600
to help it. If it helps, think of it as your pet 
dog. If it doesn't know what the instruction is,

00:27:11.600 --> 00:27:19.840
it won't know what to do. If it's never heard 
the word "JavaScript" it won't know what to say.

00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:26.240
During the past year, the huge jump in demand 
for online conferencing streaming due to

00:27:26.240 --> 00:27:31.840
COVID restrictions has put a greater demand on 
existing automated speech recognition systems.

00:27:33.200 --> 00:27:39.680
AI engineers, we've all been working really 
as fast as we can to try and make things

00:27:39.680 --> 00:27:47.600
easier, to make things available. But 
a plea: help us do so. Help us test

00:27:47.600 --> 00:27:54.080
what is out there. Help us - tell us where it 
doesn't work, because then we can change it.

00:27:56.400 --> 00:27:59.440
The focus shouldn't just be 
on speeding up the process,

00:28:00.240 --> 00:28:02.880
it needs to also be about improving accuracy.

00:28:05.760 --> 00:28:09.520
FaceBook live has been using um AI. It's been do,

00:28:09.520 --> 00:28:13.600
it's been doing away with one third of 
the components of a basic ASR system.

00:28:15.280 --> 00:28:19.280
And train, so basically, it's been getting 
rid of the pronunciation lexicon and it's

00:28:19.280 --> 00:28:26.320
training the part which identifies the individual 
constituent sounds of a word, to directly predict

00:28:26.320 --> 00:28:32.800
the characters of a word. A language model then 
determines the interrelationship of these words.

00:28:33.520 --> 00:28:38.800
Say, that frequency of use and words which are 
commonly strung together becomes what it thinks

00:28:38.800 --> 00:28:44.960
you're going to be saying. The slimming down 
and improvement of accuracy in ASR was achieved

00:28:44.960 --> 00:28:51.040
through using tools, like PyTorch, was an open 
source machine learning library derived from Torch

00:28:51.040 --> 00:28:57.840
library. Please do have a look at it. There are 
lots and lots of ways you can help improve that.

00:29:00.960 --> 00:29:08.000
Captions open up even more accessibility options.
We've already talked about the impact of captions

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:12.800
for translation. Another development 
brought through artificial intelligence

00:29:13.360 --> 00:29:18.240
is the visual images being created based 
on the descriptive text contained in that

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:25.840
caption. This is going to be our next generation 
of captioning tools. It's in its very early stages.

00:29:26.960 --> 00:29:32.480
We have AI which can produce captions 
from data contained in images, but

00:29:32.480 --> 00:29:39.040
only this week the Allen Institute for AI 
announced it had developed an AI which produces

00:29:39.040 --> 00:29:44.720
imagery created from those text captions. The 
results, for those who may not have seen them,

00:29:45.680 --> 00:29:50.000
are so far restricted from looking like 
Picasso might have knocked up in a hurry,

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:56.320
but their principle is that they generate an 
image. They allow somebody who may not be able

00:29:56.320 --> 00:30:02.000
to understand without an image added to those 
words the full context of what is being said.

00:30:02.560 --> 00:30:07.840
Or they may not be able to process it 
because their neural processing is different.

00:30:08.800 --> 00:30:15.600
This is going to take what we can do with captions 
to a whole new realm. It's going to make even more

00:30:15.600 --> 00:30:24.000
accessible information. But if you don't have 
captions, if you haven't introduced subtitling

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:29.760
into your business plans already, when this 
technology develops you won't be able to use it,

00:30:30.400 --> 00:30:38.160
because it relies on having those subtitles in the 
first place. Eventually, the work that is happening

00:30:38.160 --> 00:30:45.200
on these developments is that the final image 
will be of photographic quality with color, scale,

00:30:45.200 --> 00:30:53.600
and proportion all correctly represented. So when 
I'm talking about an apple and how that relates

00:30:53.600 --> 00:31:02.880
to a concept i'm describing, that would also appear. 
If I'm talking about a flowchart, eventually that

00:31:02.880 --> 00:31:08.880
would also appear. Again, it requires us to help 
teach it, but that is where the technology is going.

00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:16.240
A simplified explanation of that process is that 
a machine learning algorithm has been trained to

00:31:16.240 --> 00:31:23.360
recognize conceptual connections between language
and visual data. An illustration of this would be

00:31:23.360 --> 00:31:29.680
that given that text "a clock tower in the middle 
of town," the technology produces an image of a

00:31:29.680 --> 00:31:34.880
taller tower-like structure with a clock at 
the top surrounded by less high buildings.

00:31:35.680 --> 00:31:43.680
Suddenly, people are receiving the spoken word, 
the written word, and a visual representation.

00:31:43.680 --> 00:31:47.600
Just think how powerful that 
combination is going to be.

00:31:51.920 --> 00:31:57.920
We already have tools like Web Captioner.
If you are doing an event and you don't

00:31:57.920 --> 00:32:04.800
have resources to purchase live captioning 
done by humans, which is a preferred option,

00:32:06.160 --> 00:32:13.360
please look at tools like Web Captioner. There are 
other ones on the market, too. They use Google APIs

00:32:13.360 --> 00:32:21.120
generated to, to create captions, but invest the 
time. Invest the time in actually training it.

00:32:22.080 --> 00:32:28.000
We tested this in a number of WordCamps including 
WordCamp Dublin last year, and we asked all

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:36.800
speakers to practice saying a couple of sentences 
from their talk into Web Captioner. Picking

00:32:36.800 --> 00:32:43.840
the right option that successfully 
produced the text that they were saying.

00:32:44.720 --> 00:32:50.800
We also asked them to tell us the words that and 
the jargon that would not be necessarily known

00:32:50.800 --> 00:32:56.160
or that may with a strong accent sound slightly 
different to what Web Captioner had learnt

00:32:56.160 --> 00:33:04.800
already. We inputted that text into Web Captioner, 
and it was wonderful to see that in most cases

00:33:05.360 --> 00:33:12.160
that improved the captions that we produced 
to a 98% level. It didn't get everything -

00:33:12.720 --> 00:33:20.480
it still had issues. "Huddersfield" is always going 
to get - be heard wrong. It's just one of those words

00:33:20.480 --> 00:33:28.480
that captioners - an auto captioner - just does not 
get right, but it's a huge step forward. Since

00:33:28.480 --> 00:33:33.280
WordCamp Dublin there has been much more 
developments and tests in tools like this.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:42.320
Web Captioner has, in the last few weeks, released 
a beta version which you can test, and you can add

00:33:42.320 --> 00:33:48.560
to things like Zoom, to other video conferencing 
materials. We're currently doing tests on this

00:33:48.560 --> 00:33:55.440
in the WordPress Marketing and WordPress TV teams 
as well as tests with other facilities like AWS,

00:33:55.440 --> 00:34:01.920
and how we can use auto-generated captions 
from, from those facilities to then correct

00:34:01.920 --> 00:34:08.400
and start subtitling more and more videos,
and with your help making that possible.

00:34:10.160 --> 00:34:18.960
OBS, which is a open source software also now has 
a beta version of captioning. So, if you are doing

00:34:18.960 --> 00:34:25.040
a talk and you're going through OBS software 
for that talk, and connecting that to Zoom,

00:34:25.840 --> 00:34:31.920
StreamYard, whatever you're using. There is a 
beta version that you can now enable and you can,

00:34:31.920 --> 00:34:41.040
and that live auto captioning can appear. The more 
people use it, the more it will improve, but we need

00:34:41.040 --> 00:34:49.200
people to use it, test it, to give feedback, correct 
it. We need more accents to do it, we need people

00:34:49.200 --> 00:34:57.360
with more accessibility issues, to actually try 
the software. In my work, we have a number of people

00:34:57.360 --> 00:35:01.840
who have hearing difficulties who are 
actually now testing some of this software.

00:35:04.400 --> 00:35:12.160
I focused this talk on the why part of captioning.
If you've been convinced - and I hope you have -

00:35:12.160 --> 00:35:17.040
that this is something you really should be doing,
I suggest you look at the presentation slides

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:21.680
from yesterday's speaker, Meryl Evans, who's 
given a handy list of tools which you can use.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:29.840
People don't like being in 
the dark. Help put the light on.

00:35:31.120 --> 00:35:39.440
You can also do that, and make a difference by 
becoming a subtitling champion. It really is easy.

00:35:40.160 --> 00:35:45.760
I will guarantee you will learn a new skill, 
and we will help you learn that new skill.

00:35:48.320 --> 00:35:51.120
You can also play a part in knowledge sharing,

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:56.000
and the skills that you learn, and the 
knowledge that you share, is much wider

00:35:56.000 --> 00:36:01.840
than the WordPress environment, the open source 
environment. It can make a difference in your

00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:07.920
products, your company, your culture. It can make 
a difference in how we deal with information

00:36:08.880 --> 00:36:16.640
and people's access to it. Please invest in 
subtitling. Please don't put up half thought

00:36:16.640 --> 00:36:24.560
about solutions. Work out how it's going to work. 
For a lot of the, um, the camps, today's event, too,

00:36:24.560 --> 00:36:30.560
they also have another option where you can read 
subtitles that can be changed into different fonts.

00:36:31.840 --> 00:36:38.080
YouTube subtitling for live feed is really 
difficult to read. It's very difficult to process

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:44.960
if you have any kind of neuroprocessing issue. 
It can be very difficult if you just wear glasses.

00:36:48.320 --> 00:36:56.480
Support the WP diversity and tech accessibility. 
It will give you huge rewards, but it also means

00:36:56.480 --> 00:37:02.240
that the people who really need the technology 
don't have to be making that call themselves

00:37:02.240 --> 00:37:08.880
all the time. This should be something that we do 
from scratch, that we include in all our planning.

00:37:12.320 --> 00:37:15.920
Finally, tell your speakers when 
you're planning a WordCamp,

00:37:15.920 --> 00:37:21.840
or any kind of online event, or even 
in-person event when we're allowed to again.

00:37:23.680 --> 00:37:30.080
Help them understand about providing text even 
after the event so subtitles can be done quicker.

00:37:32.240 --> 00:37:38.880
Help them even commit to subtitling something 
of their own. With the auto captioning tools

00:37:38.880 --> 00:37:46.240
that now exist it doesn't have to take a huge 
amount of time. Sometimes, where it takes time is

00:37:46.240 --> 00:37:51.840
because of unfamiliarity with where the speakers 
going, what they're talking about, and the jargon.

00:37:55.120 --> 00:37:59.760
Please come and join our campaign. You 
can make a difference for inclusion,

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:05.920
diversity, and user experience. It will improve 
your organization's messaging and reach.

00:38:07.680 --> 00:38:11.360
It will make it different.
It may even help you one day.

00:38:12.720 --> 00:38:22.320
Thank you. You can find me on @NonStopNewsUK on 
Twitter. If anyone, i know i have had a lot of

00:38:22.320 --> 00:38:27.600
questions that have come in on on twitter as well 
already, um i will make sure i answer those in the

00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:33.040
next few days. And i had a request for a couple 
of people who'd like to do an interactive session

00:38:33.040 --> 00:38:39.440
learning how to use Amara and we have got those 
planned, too. So please do contact me on Twitter on

00:38:39.440 --> 00:38:46.640
@NonStopNewsUK, on Slack on abhanonstopnewsuk and, we will connect you with those things.

00:38:49.120 --> 00:38:56.400
Amanda: Okay, thank you so much Abha. That was wonderful. 
I'm so full of information. We really appreciate

00:38:56.400 --> 00:39:01.760
you sharing your expertise and breaking down the 
kinds of captions and subtitles, how essential they

00:39:01.760 --> 00:39:08.080
are to learning. Um, there was a lot of conversation 
in the the YouTube stream chat, too, and we do have

00:39:08.080 --> 00:39:15.360
some questions, that we have less, a little less 
than 10 minutes to get to, so um if you don't mind...

00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:21.440
Io the first question that i'm going to 
ask, I think the first question was, I think

00:39:21.440 --> 00:39:27.120
mostly answered in the chat, but they,
their comment was: "It's very interesting

00:39:27.120 --> 00:39:31.280
about non-English speaking countries 
having adopted captions at a greater rate.

00:39:32.160 --> 00:39:40.000
Which countries do you feel set the standard 
in terms of subtitles." Abha: The, the Spanish film

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:45.200
industry has actually been really good 
at this, and there has been some working

00:39:45.200 --> 00:39:51.600
with the, with the US as well, which is it's been 
very good in terms of how subtitles are presented.

00:39:52.400 --> 00:39:58.400
And, and, I think that has been a model that lots 
of other smaller broadcasting things have taken on.

00:39:59.840 --> 00:40:06.960
So, in terms of actual conferencing, the, where 
countries have a regulatory requirement

00:40:08.160 --> 00:40:14.640
to caption, it is worth having a look at the 
processes that they use, because they tend to

00:40:14.640 --> 00:40:22.640
be more tested, and they have tended to look at the 
various options and how they can do that. So, again

00:40:23.200 --> 00:40:28.560
America has had a lot of regulation on that. Um, 
some of the big charities have also done some ,

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:34.880
some work on that and I can share some links
after this talk, as well. Amanda: Okay, perfect, thank you.

00:40:35.520 --> 00:40:42.560
Um, the next question is: "SEO and YouTube are hidden 
gems for building our online footprint, as you

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:51.840
uh, mentioned, and are there, um, sorry are there 
rules for effective content for web pages, links,

00:40:51.840 --> 00:40:59.520
etc., for captioning, to help videos rank higher, 
or rank more?" Abha: There's a lot of work going on at

00:40:59.520 --> 00:41:06.880
the moment um in terms of readability of captions, 
and there's some work that's been pioneering in, in

00:41:06.880 --> 00:41:13.840
Switzerland about actually how algorithms can 
give a higher rating to captions that are readable.

00:41:14.480 --> 00:41:22.800
So, captions that come in huge blocks of text with 
no punctuation, would be, would have a lower, um

00:41:23.680 --> 00:41:28.960
reach. And so there are some testing that's 
going on with a couple of the, the big providers,

00:41:28.960 --> 00:41:36.400
for how that can be be more promoted. And you'll 
notice that some automatic translation things,

00:41:36.400 --> 00:41:43.280
particularly YouTube, misses out punctuation. And 
say, when people are then watching the video back,

00:41:43.280 --> 00:41:48.960
actually the, the bots are not understanding what's 
being said, because there's no punctuation to

00:41:48.960 --> 00:41:54.480
help them. So, if you put punctuation in, that does 
increase the searchability of that, and the ranking.

00:41:55.920 --> 00:42:02.560
Amanda: Okay, great, now that's helpful, helpful to know. 
Okay, got a little more than five minutes. Um,

00:42:02.560 --> 00:42:06.640
make sure if you do have any other questions, um, 
to throw them in the chat. But the next question

00:42:06.640 --> 00:42:13.280
for you, Abha, of that, is: "What is your opinion in 
delaying audio and video signal at live events in

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:20.560
order to give more time to live transcribers or AI 
tools to be correct with the subtitles or captions,

00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:27.840
and deliver them synchronized?" Abha: I think it's 
a really big problem. I think, just looking at

00:42:27.840 --> 00:42:33.520
today's, I know my screen over here, which has been 
live, has been quite behind what I've been doing.

00:42:33.520 --> 00:42:38.640
A lot of the, um, the software like OBS has a 
real issue with this, because it creates a delay

00:42:38.640 --> 00:42:44.640
between video and, um, and what you're actually 
saying, which causes a difficulty for anybody

00:42:44.640 --> 00:42:49.200
who's lip reading, because they're lip 
reading something that is then out of context

00:42:49.200 --> 00:42:55.760
with what's behind them, or what you're actually 
trying to emphasize, so they could see an emphasis

00:42:56.560 --> 00:43:01.520
on something that is actually no longer 
being talked about. So, um, I think that

00:43:01.520 --> 00:43:07.680
as events, and as we become more online events, 
we need to think about the, putting a delay in.

00:43:07.680 --> 00:43:14.720
But we also need to do some simpler things, 
like encouraging, um, text to be available.

00:43:15.520 --> 00:43:20.080
The, the captioners will work a lot quicker 
if they know what jargon is going to be used.

00:43:20.960 --> 00:43:28.320
So, Word, WordCamp London, our live captioners are, 
um, very accurate. And one of the reasons for that

00:43:28.320 --> 00:43:34.640
accuracy is because they have the jargon, and 
the terminology, and, it's quite often, the talk

00:43:34.640 --> 00:43:40.160
words from similar speakers, and that means that 
they don't have to build in that extra delay for

00:43:40.160 --> 00:43:45.120
everything to catch up again. It still doesn't 
avoid the internet delay that you will have,

00:43:45.120 --> 00:43:52.320
with video, but there are easy fixes most of the 
software, particularly the paid-for software, does

00:43:52.320 --> 00:43:59.680
actually allow you to compensate for that delay. 
And I think there is an expectation now that, um,

00:44:00.240 --> 00:44:04.880
particularly in the commercial world, and maybe 
it needs to come to the, the open source, too,

00:44:04.880 --> 00:44:08.720
is that if you're putting on an event, 
help train your speakers in how to do that.

00:44:09.600 --> 00:44:14.080
Because otherwise, you will have people who are, 
regardless of what you do in regards to the

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:21.840
delay that you put in, their camera may still be 
adding in several seconds of the delay in addition.

00:44:22.960 --> 00:44:26.240
Amanda: Right. Okay, okay, thank you for that response.